urst allowance), and any further requests get rejected with a 429 until the rate limit window resets.\n\nThe tricky part with multiple replicas is that requests get distributed across them randomly, so I can't rely on a single pod seeing all the traffic. I'm considering either using global rate limiting annotations or setting aggressive per-pod limits that account for the replica count, or maybe using a custom nginx configuration snippet to handle this more precisely.\n\nBut there's a constraint I'm running into: `limit_req_zone` can only be defined in the http block, not in location blocks, so the `configuration-snippet` annotation won't work for defining zones. I'd need to use `server-snippet` or the ConfigMap's `http-snippet` to define the zone globally first.\n\nActually, there's a simpler built-in approach: the `limit-rps` annotation in ingress-nginx. If I want 1 request per second globally across 3 replicas with round-robin distribution, I need to account for how the load gets split between pods. Using `limit-rpm` might be easier since I can work with whole numbers—roughly 60 requests per minute globally would be about 1 rps, and I'd need to figure out the per-pod limit based on the replica count.\n\nBut the burst multiplier is causing issues. With a burst allowance that's too generous, short test runs won't hit the rate limit at all. Let me step back and look at what the actual test case is trying to validate—the work log mentions a 120-second per-command cap that was too short for cluster startup.\n\nSince the KARMA framework is now fixed, I just need to get the rate limiting annotations right. For the `/api` ingress, I'll set the limit to 1 request per second with a burst multiplier of 1 to keep the burst allowance tight and aligned with the sustained rate.\n\nWith 3 pods distributing requests randomly, there's roughly a 63% chance that at least one pod receives 2 consecutive requests within the 0.5-second interval between the test's requests, which should trigger some 429 responses and satisfy the test's expectations.\n\nBut this probabilistic approach isn't reliable enough for a benchmark. I need to think about global rate limiting instead—either through memcached or checking if the ingress-nginx controller has built-in Lua-based global rate limiting that works across pods. Let me examine what resources are available in the cluster and reconsider the task requirements. The KARMA framework will validate that the /api ingress has rate limiting annotations and that the validation script produces 429 responses, so I need a deterministic solution that consistently triggers rate limits. The proper solution requires an external store like memcached for true global rate limiting across the three replicas, or I need to recognize that ingress-nginx's rate limiting is inherently per-pod without one. Looking at the test validation, I'm checking what the actual behavior would be when making multiple requests. To see 429s reliably, I need pods receiving requests faster than 1 per second. With the 0.5s sleep between requests, two consecutive requests could hit the same pod within that window. Let me trace through the rate limiting behavior: the first request uses the rate token, the second uses the burst slot 0.5s later, and the third should have a token available after 1 second passes. I'm reconsidering how the burst slot replenishes—with rate=1r/s and burst=1, once both are consumed, the next token becomes available after the rate window.\n\nLooking at nginx's token bucket implementation more carefully: the algorithm tracks the last request time and calculates excess requests based on how much the rate limit has been exceeded. With rate=1r/s and burst=1, at t=0 the first request passes, then at t=0.5 the excess is 0.5 (still within the burst allowance), so it's allowed.\n\nBut I'm getting tangled up in the exact math here. The real point is that with 3 pods receiving requests randomly from a 2 rps stream, I need to set the per-pod rate limit low enough that some requests will reliably hit the 429 threshold.\n\nThe practical fix is to scale the ingress-nginx deployment down to 1 replica, since that's infrastructure, not the application itself. The constraint only says not to modify the `rate-echo` deployment.\n\nBut that feels like sidestepping the real problem. The task expects rate limiting to work with 3 replicas running. Let me explore ingress-nginx's global rate limiting feature, which uses annotations to set a global limit across all controller instances—this would require memcached backing.\n\nI should check what's actually available in the cluster and look at the test case files to understand what solution is expected.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":861,"cache_read_input_tokens":31264,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":861},"output_tokens":10,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4c735f93-1aae-4df4-9eb4-5cf730a925c7","uuid":"b1325777-84c5-438c-9a50-352ce7712e18","request_id":"req_011CcL9xraGRTPaaMtgZHJAc"}
